title: For Sale:  1907 Colt Police Positive (New Police) .32 cal
postcontent: Very nice Colt Police Positive manufactured in 1907. This particular model is an interesting transitional piece. The New Police .32 revolver was manufactured until 1907 and was then replaced with the improved Police Positive with the improvements in the internals. Colt continued to use up their supply of New Police .32 barrels and simply stamped Police Positive on the other side until the supply was gone. Gun is tight. Bluing is in great condition for age with some light wear around the muzzle. Bore is excellent. Sorry no trades.

Stock: Custom- dual pillar bedding, free floating barrel 
Sights: Drilled and tapped for scope mounts 
Rifling Rate of Twist: 308 Win(1 in 10") 

Location: Los Angeles, S.Bay

Price: $1200.00 

Will ship (Y/N): Yes, buyer pays shipping and insurance to FFL

Kurt's Kustom Firearms (FL), TechniCarbon Dynamics "TEK2000" stock, dual pillar bedded, full floating barrel, adjustable aluminum recoil pad and adjustable cheek rest. Unfortunately you can't get these stocks anymore as Kurt Wala passed away in 2009. Excellent quality stock from a real craftsman.

Tasco Tactical 8-40x56mm scope, made in Hakko, Japan. These are the good ones, super clear glass, good light transmittance. They mount these on 50BMGs when you really want to reach out and touch someone. Includes 2 sun shades and Leupold rings/bases.

Harris type bipod included.

Will also include an SKB foam padded plastic/metal hard case with roller wheels and laser bore sight (unopened).

I only have 20 rds through it. I was just starting to break in the barrel, cleaned it but then got into other things and this has been sitting in the closet unused. It's basically brand new. The stock is weighted so with the scope this setup is hefty at 15lbs. It's more of a bench rest rifle. This model is before the AccuTrigger so no adjustable trigger. Not sure what the pull weight is. No issues whatsoever with anything I've listed. Prefer FFL/PPT at local dealer in the Los Angeles/OC area. I would consider trades (or trades + cash) of equal value for Glocks 19, 26 or 27 or other 9mm and 40 cal semi auto handguns. Please be reasonable with your trade offers and not lowball. I have over $1500 into this setup.
Thanks for looking.

A bit more info on the scope pulled from other forums...

Tasco Tactical TAC840x56 scope made in Japan by Hakko. This is a military contract scope for the US NAVY and has excellent optics. Hakko also made scopes for Israeli Military. This scope has a 30MM tube with 2 sunshades. This is a High Quality scope Great for tactical, targer or sniper. 8 To 40 Power and 10 YDS - 400 YDS to infinity.

This is a very good scope if it is the mil dot reticle. I ran into one years ago when looking for a target scope for a Remington 700 PSS. Hakko made some very nice scopes including the Springfield model I ended up getting for that rifle. Back then it was about 800 dollars. Back when 800 bucks bought you a high end scope. I don't know how much it is being sold for, I am assuming you have seen one advertised? I know the military contracted with Hakko to make some sniper scopes which I believe were this model. I believe it was the Navy that ordered some. I know the Israeli military also contracted with this manufacturer. They are rugged and reliable. They were used on Barrett .50 cal rifles. They had glass etched reticles and were built to take abuse. The optics were superb for long range shooting. I doubt you are looking to shoot that 1000 yard shot but you can with this scope. I don't remember exactly but the parallax may only adjust down to 10 meters. Hakko was a good manufacturer so if the price is cheap enough it may be a great buy.

postcontent:
LNIB Px4 Storm 9mm. Black finish. This is Type F config which functions the same as the Model 92FS. Can be modified easily to a Type G with Beretta's factory kit, so that it becomes a decocker only pistol instead of a decocker/safety pistol.

Comes with the two factory 17 round mags, plus an additional two 20 rounders that I bought (they are a very nice fit and don't extend much, makes a great mag to have loaded in for the nightstand) valued at 50 dollars each. The Storm mags are extremely high quality like most any Beretta handgun mags, made by MecGar in Italy.

This pistol has hardly any recoil with the rotating barrel design. Everything about it is just very smooth and well made, the slide racks very easily, it recoils extremely softly, it is lights out accurate and the DA/SA trigger on it is superb and easily compares to the DA/SA on a Sig Sauer. Single action is very light and crisp, lends itself very well to fast and accurate fire. Double action is about 10 pounds, but feels ridiculously smooth, it is very easy to keep it on target during the DA pull.

I love everything about this gun and I regret feeling the need to sell it at this point in time, so I hope it goes to a good owner. Asking 500 firm for the package, that is a great price given the expensive 20 round mags are included. Has original case and everything, all three backstraps included, mag loader included, Beretta factory paperwork. This is essentially still a new gun.

I know everyone watches Pawn Stars and Dickerin' these days so let me just say it again: price is 500 firm, I've already haggled ahead of time and am giving you a fair market price for the package. I won't debundle the mags and sell you just the pistol by itself or anything like that. 500 gets the gun, all four mags, all original Beretta factory 'stuff'.

title: For Sale:  Surplus Body Armor (German, E. German, USGI)
postcontent:
I have some surplus armor for sale.
First off, 4 German-made Flecktarn frag vests. They were available for a while but the surplus is now dried up (they probably sent what was left as aid to the middle east). These vests are relatively light, comfortable and have great coverage. Ballistic protection is surprisingly good, perhaps about IIa equivalent based upon some less-than-scientific testing.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NA-A_i3pJGc
People have also used them as plate carriers, sewing pouches on the inside. That way you get AR500 front and back with fragmentation protection on your sides and neck.
They're also good for airsofting, costumes, collecting, etc.

Of the 4 I have, 2 are ""Large" and 2 are "Extra Large". All have 1995 production dates except one of the XLs is 1996.

Asking 60$ each. Can ship for extra.

Item #2 is a Vietnam War-era M69 frag vest. It's made of ballistic nylon so it is quite heavy. I couldn't recommend using it for your SHTF stash, but people do collect these things and use them for re-enactments. The outer vest is in pretty good shape with only very small rips. The Nylon itself looks to be in great shape.

Asking 150$

Item #3 is a pair of E. German M59 Stalhelms. These are post-war examples with heavily sloped edges to increase the chance of deflecting incoming fire. As far as steel helmets go they offer the best ballistic protection. PASGTs are still better, but aren't as cheap.

Asking 30$ each.
